From: Duncan Maitland <me@duncm.com>
Subject: socket: pick the recvmsg() signature by LINUX_VERSION_CODE

Upstream commit a4289db5 ("socket: use IP_TUNNEL_RECURSION_LIMIT for
recvmsg definition") tries to detect whether the kernel still has the
'int *addr_len' parameter on struct proto::recvmsg by testing whether
the IP_TUNNEL_RECURSION_LIMIT macro is defined.

That heuristic is incorrect.  IP_TUNNEL_RECURSION_LIMIT was added by
the unrelated commit 6f1a9140ecda ("net: add xmit recursion limit to
tunnel xmit functions"), which has been backported to recent stable
trees (e.g. Debian's 6.12.85+deb13-arm64 kernel) -- so the macro is
defined on plenty of kernels that still expect the 5-argument
recvmsg() form.  The result is a build failure of the form:

    socket.c:2847:28: error: initialization of
        'int (*)(struct sock *, struct msghdr *, size_t, int, int *)'
        from incompatible pointer type
        'int (*)(struct sock *, struct msghdr *, size_t, int)'
            .recvmsg = quic_recvmsg,
                       ^~~~~~~~~~~~

The 'int *addr_len' argument was actually removed by Linux commit
8341c989ac77 ("net: remove addr_len argument of recvmsg() handlers"),
which first appeared in v7.1-rc1.  Kernels strictly older than 7.1.0
therefore still want the 5-argument form, regardless of whether
IP_TUNNEL_RECURSION_LIMIT happens to be defined.

Use LINUX_VERSION_CODE >= KERNEL_VERSION(7, 1, 0) directly so that the
correct prototype is chosen on every kernel.  <linux/version.h> is
already included at the top of socket.c, so no extra header is needed.

---
 modules/net/quic/socket.c | 11 ++++++++++-
 1 file changed, 10 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

--- a/modules/net/quic/socket.c
+++ b/modules/net/quic/socket.c
@@ -1281,7 +1281,16 @@ static int quic_wait_for_packet(struct sock *sk, struct list_head *head, u32 fla
 	return err;
 }
 
-#ifdef IP_TUNNEL_RECURSION_LIMIT
+/*
+ * The 'int *addr_len' parameter was removed from struct proto::recvmsg by
+ * Linux commit 8341c989ac77 ("net: remove addr_len argument of recvmsg()
+ * handlers"), which first appeared in v7.1-rc1.  Earlier kernels still
+ * expect the 5-argument form.  Upstream's IP_TUNNEL_RECURSION_LIMIT proxy
+ * misfires on stable kernels (e.g. Debian Trixie's 6.12.x) that have
+ * backported the unrelated tunnel recursion limit but not the recvmsg
+ * ABI change, so detect the version directly instead.
+ */
+#if LINUX_VERSION_CODE >= KERNEL_VERSION(7, 1, 0)
 static int quic_recvmsg(struct sock *sk, struct msghdr *msg, size_t msg_len,
 			int flags)
 #else
